# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mann-whitney
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The **Mann–Whitney U test** (also called the **Mann–Whitney–Wilcoxon** (**MWW/MWU**), **Wilcoxon rank-sum test**, or **Wilcoxon–Mann–Whitney test**) is a nonparametric statistical test of the null hypothesis that randomly selected values *X* and *Y* from two populations have the same distribution.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The value of *U* calculated by the test can be converted to a measure of effect size by dividing it by the maximum value of U, which is the product of the sizes of the two samples being compared.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] This measure is the probability that the value of a random observation from the higher group will be greater than that of a random observation from the lower group.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Nonparametric tests used on two *dependent* samples are the sign test and the Wilcoxon signed-rank test.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Henry Mann and Donald Ransom Whitney developed the Mann–Whitney *U* test under the assumption of continuous responses with the alternative hypothesis being that one distribution is stochastically greater than the other.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] That is to say that the probability of a random observation from one group being larger than a random observation from the other group is 0.5.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] There are many other ways to formulate the null and alternative hypotheses such that the Mann–Whitney *U* test will give a valid test.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Under the null hypothesis *H*0, the distributions of both populations are identical.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The alternative hypothesis *H*1 is that the distributions are not identical.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Under more strict assumptions than the general formulation above, e.g., if the responses are assumed to be continuous and the alternative is restricted to a shift in location, i.e., *F*1(*x*) = *F*2(*x* + *δ*), we can interpret a significant Mann–Whitney *U* test as showing a difference in medians.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] This, however, is an interpretation, and is not the actual hypothesis being tested (see above).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] This practice relies on strict assumptions about the data distribution.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] When this assumption does not hold, it is simple to demonstrate that the test produces a statistically significant result when the medians of the two groups are in fact identical.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] If a test of medians is required, quantile regression explicitly tests this.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Under this location shift assumption, we can also interpret the Mann–Whitney *U* test as assessing whether the Hodges–Lehmann estimate of the difference in central tendency between the two populations differs from zero.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The Hodges–Lehmann estimate for this two-sample problem is the median of all possible differences between an observation in the first sample and an observation in the second sample.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Otherwise, if both the dispersions and shapes of the distribution of both samples differ, the Mann–Whitney *U* test fails a test of medians.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] It is possible to show examples where medians are numerically equal while the test rejects the null hypothesis with a small p-value.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The Mann–Whitney *U* test / Wilcoxon rank-sum test is not the same as the Wilcoxon *signed*-rank test, although both are nonparametric and involve summation of ranks.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The Mann–Whitney *U* test is applied to independent samples.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The Wilcoxon signed-rank test is applied to matched or dependent samples.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Although Mann and Whitney's original paper described the test as one of stochastic superiority – in other words, as a test of whether an observation from one group was likely to be larger than an observation from the other group, the test statistic, *U*, does not give this probability.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] This probability can be simply calculated by dividing *U* by its maximum value, which is the product of the two sample sizes.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Let $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n_{1}}$ be group 1, an i.i.d. sample from X , and $Y_{1},\ldots ,Y_{n_{2}}$ be group 2, an i.i.d. sample from Y , and let both samples be independent of each other.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Note that this is the same definition as the common language effect size, i.e. the probability that a classifier will rank a randomly chosen instance from the first group higher than a randomly chosen instance from the second group.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] AUC*k*,*k* will always be zero but, unlike in the two-class case, generally AUC*k*,*ℓ* ≠ AUC*ℓ*,*k*, which is why the *M* measure sums over all (*k*,*ℓ*) pairs, in effect using the average of AUC*k*,*ℓ* and AUC*ℓ*,*k*.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Alternatively, the null distribution can be approximated using permutation tests and Monte Carlo simulations.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Some books tabulate statistics equivalent to *U*, such as the sum of ranks in one of the samples, rather than *U* itself.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The Mann–Whitney *U* test is included in most statistical packages.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] It is also easily calculated by hand, especially for small samples.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] For comparing two small sets of observations, a direct method is quick, and gives insight into the meaning of the *U* statistic, which corresponds to the number of wins out of all pairwise contests (see the tortoise and hare example under Examples below).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] For each observation in one set, count the number of times this first value wins over any observations in the other set (the other value loses if this first is larger).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The sum of wins and ties is *U* (i.e., $U_{1}$ ) for the first set.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] *U* for the other set is the converse (i.e., $U_{2}$ ).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Now, add up the ranks for the observations which came from sample 1.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The sum of ranks in sample 2 is now determined, since the sum of all the ranks equals *N*(*N* + 1)/2 where *N* is the total number of observations.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Note that it doesn't matter which of the two samples is considered sample 1.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] is the one used when consulting significance tables.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The maximum value of *U* is the product of the sample sizes for the two samples (i.e., $U_{i}=n_{1}n_{2}$ ).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] In such a case, the "other" *U* would be 0.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Suppose that Aesop is dissatisfied with his classic experiment in which one tortoise was found to beat one hare in a race, and decides to carry out a significance test to discover whether the results could be extended to tortoises and hares in general.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] He collects a sample of 6 tortoises and 6 hares, and makes them all run his race at once.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Rank the animals by the time they take to complete the course, so give the first animal home rank 12, the second rank 11, and so forth.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] In practice some of this information may already have been supplied and common sense should be used in deciding whether to repeat it.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] "Outcomes of the two treatments were compared using the Wilcoxon–Mann–Whitney two-sample rank-sum test.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The treatment effect (difference between treatments) was quantified using the Hodges–Lehmann (HL) estimator, which is consistent with the Wilcoxon test.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] This estimator (HLΔ) is the median of all possible differences in outcomes between a subject in group B and a subject in group A.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] A non-parametric 0.95 confidence interval for HLΔ accompanies these estimates as does ρ, an estimate of the probability that a randomly chosen subject from population B has a higher weight than a randomly chosen subject from population A.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The median [quartiles] weight for subjects on treatment A and B respectively are 147 [121, 177] and 151 [130, 180] kg.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] However it would be rare to find such an extensive report in a document whose major topic was not statistical inference.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] For large samples, *U* is approximately normally distributed.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] where *m**U* and *σ**U* are the mean and standard deviation of *U*, is approximately a standard normal deviate whose significance can be checked in tables of the normal distribution.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The formula for the standard deviation is more complicated in the presence of tied ranks.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] where the left side is simply the variance and the right side is the adjustment for ties, *t**k* is the number of ties for the *k*th rank, and *K* is the total number of unique ranks with ties.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] If the number of ties is small (and especially if there are no large tie bands) ties can be ignored when doing calculations by hand.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The computer statistical packages will use the correctly adjusted formula as a matter of routine.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Note that since *U*1 + *U*2 = *n*1*n*2, the mean *n*1*n*2/2 used in the normal approximation is the mean of the two values of *U*.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Therefore, the absolute value of the *z*-statistic calculated will be same whichever value of *U* is used.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] It is a widely recommended practice for scientists to report an effect size for an inferential test.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] One method of reporting the effect size for the Mann–Whitney *U* test is with *f*, the common language effect size.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] As a sample statistic, the common language effect size is computed by forming all possible pairs between the two groups, then finding the proportion of pairs that support a direction (say, that items from group 1 are larger than items from group 2).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] To illustrate, in a study with a sample of ten hares and ten tortoises, the total number of ordered pairs is ten times ten or 100 pairs of hares and tortoises.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Suppose the results show that the hare ran faster than the tortoise in 90 of the 100 sample pairs; in that case, the sample common language effect size is 90%.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] This is the same as the area under the curve (AUC) for the ROC curve.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] A statistic called *ρ* that is linearly related to *U* and widely used in studies of categorization (discrimination learning involving concepts), and elsewhere, is calculated by dividing *U* by its maximum value for the given sample sizes, which is simply *n*1×*n*2.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] *ρ* is thus a non-parametric measure of the overlap between two distributions; it can take values between 0 and 1, and it estimates P(*Y* > *X*) + 0.5 P(*Y* = *X*), where *X* and *Y* are randomly chosen observations from the two distributions.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Both extreme values represent complete separation of the distributions, while a *ρ* of 0.5 represents complete overlap.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] A method of reporting the effect size for the Mann–Whitney *U* test is with a measure of rank correlation known as the rank-biserial correlation.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Edward Cureton introduced and named the measure.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Like other correlational measures, the rank-biserial correlation can range from minus one to plus one, with a value of zero indicating no relationship.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] There is a simple difference formula to compute the rank-biserial correlation from the common language effect size: the correlation is the difference between the proportion of pairs favorable to the hypothesis (*f*) minus its complement (i.e., the proportion that is unfavorable (*u*)).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] For example, consider the example where hares run faster than tortoises in 90 of 100 pairs.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The common language effect size is 90%, so the rank-biserial correlation is 90% minus 10%, and the rank-biserial *r* = 0.80.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] This formula is useful when the data are not available, but when there is a published report, because *U* and the sample sizes are routinely reported.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Using the example above with 90 pairs that favor the hares and 10 pairs that favor the tortoise, *U*2 is the smaller of the two, so *U2* = 10.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] This formula then gives *r* = 1 – (2×10) / (10×10) = 0.80, which is the same result as with the simple difference formula above.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] In contrast, a t-test tests a null hypothesis of equal means in two groups against an alternative of unequal means.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Hence, except in special cases, the Mann–Whitney *U* test and the t-test do not test the same hypotheses and should be compared with this in mind.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] but not interval scaled, in which case the spacing between adjacent values of the scale cannot be assumed to be constant.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] control when data are both heteroscedastic and non-normal.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] This comparison in efficiency, however, should be interpreted with caution, as Mann–Whitney and the t-test do not test the same quantities.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] If, for example, a difference of group means is of primary interest, Mann–Whitney is not an appropriate test.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The Mann–Whitney *U* test will give very similar results to performing an ordinary parametric two-sample *t*-test on the rankings of the data.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The Mann–Whitney *U* test is not valid for testing the null hypothesis $P(Y>X)+0.5P(Y=X)=0.5$ against the alternative hypothesis $P(Y>X)+0.5P(Y=X)\neq 0.5$ , without assuming that the distributions are the same under the null hypothesis (i.e., assuming $F_{1}=F_{2}$ ).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] To test between those hypotheses, better tests are available.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Among those are the Brunner-Munzel and the Fligner–Policello test.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Specifically, under the more general null hypothesis $P(Y>X)+0.5P(Y=X)=0.5$ , the Mann–Whitney *U* test can have inflated type I error rates even in large samples (especially if the variances of two populations are unequal and the sample sizes are different), a problem the better alternatives solve.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] As a result, it has been suggested to use one of the alternatives (specifically the Brunner–Munzel test) if it cannot be assumed that the distributions are equal under the null hypothesis.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] If one desires a simple shift interpretation, the Mann–Whitney *U* test should *not* be used when the distributions of the two samples are very different, as it can give erroneous interpretation of significant results.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] In that situation, the unequal variances version of the *t*-test may give more reliable results.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] *Practical Nonparametric Statistics -- 3rd ed*.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] ISBN 0-471-16068-7.*) suggest transforming the data to ranks (if they are not already ranks) and then performing the *t*-test on the transformed data, the version of the *t*-test used depending on whether or not the population variances are suspected to be different.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Rank transformations do not preserve variances, but variances are recomputed from samples after rank transformations.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The Brown–Forsythe test has been suggested as an appropriate non-parametric equivalent to the *F*-test for equal variances.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] A more powerful test is the Brunner-Munzel test, outperforming the Mann–Whitney *U* test in case of violated assumption of exchangeability.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The Mann–Whitney *U* test is a special case of the proportional odds model, allowing for covariate-adjustment.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The Mann–Whitney *U* test is related to a number of other non-parametric statistical procedures.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] For example, it is equivalent to Kendall's tau correlation coefficient if one of the variables is binary (that is, it can only take two values).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] In many software packages, the Mann–Whitney *U* test (of the hypothesis of equal distributions against appropriate alternatives) has been poorly documented.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] Some packages incorrectly treat ties or fail to document asymptotic techniques (e.g., correction for continuity).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] The statistic appeared in a 1914 article by the German Gustav Deuchler (with a missing term in the variance).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] In a single paper in 1945, Frank Wilcoxon proposed both the one-sample signed rank and the two-sample rank sum test, in a test of significance with a point null-hypothesis against its complementary alternative (that is, equal versus not equal).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] However, he only tabulated a few points for the equal-sample size case in that paper (though in a later paper he gave larger tables).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] A thorough analysis of the statistic, which included a recurrence allowing the computation of tail probabilities for arbitrary sample sizes and tables for sample sizes of eight or less appeared in the article by Henry Mann and his student Donald Ransom Whitney in 1947.
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] This article discussed alternative hypotheses, including a stochastic ordering (where the cumulative distribution functions satisfied the pointwise inequality *F**X*(*t*) < *F**Y*(*t*)).
[src:mann-whitney/mann-whitney-u-test] This paper also computed the first four moments and established the limiting normality of the statistic under the null hypothesis, so establishing that it is asymptotically distribution-free.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] The first meaning of *nonparametric* involves techniques that do not rely on data belonging to any particular parametric family of probability distributions.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] An example is order statistics, which are based on ordinal ranking of observations.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] The discussion following is taken from *Kendall's Advanced Theory of Statistics*.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] The second meaning of *nonparametric* involves techniques that do not assume that the *structure* of a model is fixed.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Typically, the model grows in size to accommodate the complexity of the data.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] In these techniques, individual variables *are* typically assumed to belong to parametric distributions, and assumptions about the types of associations among variables are also made.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Nonparametric methods are widely used for studying populations that have a ranked order (such as movie reviews receiving one to five "stars").
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] The use of nonparametric methods may be necessary when data have a ranking but no clear numerical interpretation, such as when assessing preferences.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] In terms of levels of measurement, nonparametric methods result in ordinal data.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] As nonparametric methods make fewer assumptions, their applicability is much more general than the corresponding parametric methods.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] In particular, they may be applied in situations where less is known about the application in question.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Also, due to the reliance on fewer assumptions, nonparametric methods are more robust.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Nonparametric methods are sometimes considered simpler to use and more robust than parametric methods, even when the assumptions of parametric methods are justified.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] This is due to their more general nature, which may make them less susceptible to misuse and misunderstanding.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Nonparametric methods can be considered a conservative choice, as they will work even when their assumptions are not met, whereas parametric methods can produce misleading results when their assumptions are violated.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] The wider applicability and increased robustness of nonparametric tests comes at a cost: in cases where a parametric test's assumptions are met, nonparametric tests have less statistical power.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] In other words, a larger sample size can be required to draw conclusions with the same degree of confidence.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] In mathematical statistics, nonparametric models are considered models that do not rely on a parametric assumption of the unknown data distribution (in density estimation problems) or of the regression function (in regression problems).
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] While the goal of any parametric model is the estimation of a finite number of parameters $\theta _{1},\dots ,\theta _{p}\in \mathbb {R}$ , nonparametric models aim to directly estimate the data distribution/regression function.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Relevant questions in this field regard the construction of reasonable estimators, consistency, rates of convergence and their optimality, and adaptive estimation.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] As in parametric statistics, a desirable property for an estimator ${\hat {f_{n}}}$ is that it converges to the target function f as the sample size n goes to infinity, that is, the approximation error converges to zero.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Usually, the approximation is measured in terms of $L^{2}$ -norm distance between ${\hat {f_{n}}}$ and f .
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] If an estimator is consistent for all square-integrable f , then it is called **universally consistent**.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Many common nonparametric estimators are weakly universally consistent, for example, the Nadarya-Watson estimator, kNNs and certain local polynomial estimators.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] A central topic in the statistical analysis of nonparametric estimators is their speed of convergence towards the true target function f and whether the speed is optimal, i.e., the convergence is as fast as possible.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] The most common way to measure the speed of convergence of an estimator is the minimax convergence rate, which considers the expected loss of the estimator in the worst case scenario.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Under certain assumptions on the smoothness of f , one can show that there is a minimal convergence rates that no estimator can undercut, and so any estimator achieving this minimal rate is called optimal.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] The detailed analysis of nonparametric estimators then separates into the estimation of probability densities and regressions functions.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Minimax lower bounds are known for different pairs of function classes ${\mathcal {F}}$ and comparison metrics L .
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] In fact, the Hölder spaces and the Sobolev spaces are special cases of some Besov spaces, namely $C^{\alpha }({\mathcal {X}})=B_{\infty ,\infty }^{\alpha }({\mathcal {X}})$ for $\alpha \notin \mathbb {Z}$ and $H^{s}({\mathcal {X}})=B_{2,2}^{s}({\mathcal {X}})$ .
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Thus, it often suffices to derive lower bounds under Besov-smoothness assumptions.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] By Scheffé's theorem, the total variation distance $\mathrm {TV} (\mathbb {P} _{f},\mathbb {P} _{g})$ is equivalent to the $L^{1}$ -distance of f and g .
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] The nonparametric rate is thus slower than the parametric rate $n^{-1}$ , especially in large dimensions, and approaches the parametric rate as the smoothness of the density tends to infinity.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Kernel density estimators, for instance, achieve the lower bound w.r.t. the MISE under a Sobolev hypothesis class under an appropriate bandwidth choice and is thus minimax optimal.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] More recently, also score-based generative models have been shown to achieve minimax convergence rates in total variation and in Wasserstein-1 distance for $B_{p,q}^{s}([0,1]^{d})$ -smooth distributions, $s>(1/p-1/2)_{+}$ , that are bounded away from zero from below.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Typically, the independent variables $X_{i}$ are assumed to have values in the unit cube $[0,1]^{d}$ and to be either determinsitic points on a grid (deterministic design) or uniformly distributed (random design).
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] The above setting applies to binary classification as well.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Indeed, many classification methods are of that form, for example logistic regression, linear discriminant analysis, quadratic discriminant analysis, and k-nearest-neighbors, and support vector machines.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Under certain technical assumptions, the following lower bounds are known.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Instead, one is interested in methods that achieve the minimax optimal convergence rates not only for one specific smoothness parameter, but across different values.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Adaptive estimators are often realized by taking estimators that are minimax optimal for a family of hypothesis classes and by estimating the hyperparameters via a higher-level procedure, such as unbiased risk estimation or cross-validation.
[src:mann-whitney/nonparametric-statistics] Early nonparametric statistics include the median (13th century or earlier, use in estimation by Edward Wright, 1599; see Median § History) and the sign test by John Arbuthnot (1710) in analyzing the human sex ratio at birth (see Sign test § History).
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] In statistics, the *k*th **order statistic** of a statistical sample is equal to its *k*th-smallest value.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Given a sample of size n , the *k*th order statistic is denoted $x_{(k)}$ , with $1\leq k\leq n$ .
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Together with rank statistics, order statistics are among the most fundamental tools in non-parametric statistics and inference.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Important special cases of the order statistics are the minimum and maximum value of a sample, and (with some qualifications discussed below) the sample median and other sample quantiles.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] When using probability theory to analyze order statistics of random samples from a continuous distribution, the cumulative distribution function is used to reduce the analysis to the case of order statistics of the uniform distribution.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] For example, suppose that four numbers are observed or recorded, resulting in a sample of size 4.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] where, following a common convention, we use upper-case letters to refer to random variables, and lower-case letters (as above) to refer to their actual observed values.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The sample range is the difference between the maximum and minimum.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] A similar important statistic in exploratory data analysis that is simply related to the order statistics is the sample interquartile range.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The sample median may or may not be an order statistic, since there is a single middle value only when the number *n* of observations is odd.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] More precisely, if *n* = 2*m*+1 for some integer *m*, then the sample median is $X_{(m+1)}$ and so is an order statistic.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] On the other hand, when *n* is even, *n* = 2*m* and there are two middle values, $X_{(m)}$ and $X_{(m+1)}$ , and the sample median is some function of the two (usually the average) and hence not an order statistic.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Similar remarks apply to all sample quantiles.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The case where the random variables $X_{1},X_{2},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are independent and identically distributed is treated below.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] In general, $X_{1},X_{2},\ldots ,X_{n}$ can arise by sampling from more than one population.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Then we consider the case where they are independent, but not necessarily identically distributed, and their joint probability distribution is given by the Bapat–Beg theorem.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] From now on, we will assume that the random variables under consideration are continuous and, where convenient, we will also assume that they have a probability density function (PDF), that is, they are absolutely continuous.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The peculiarities of the analysis of distributions assigning mass to points (in particular, discrete distributions) are discussed at the end.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] In the case that $X_{(j)}$ is the largest order statistic $\leq x$ , there has to be j samples $\leq x$ (each with an independent probability of $F_{X}(x)$ ) and $n-j$ samples $>x$ (each with an independent probability of $1-F_{X}(x)$ ).
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Finally there are ${\textstyle {\binom {n}{j}}}$ different ways of choosing which of the n samples are of the $\leq x$ kind.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Moreover, there are two special cases, which have CDFs that are easy to compute.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Which can be derived by careful consideration of probabilities.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] In this section we show that the order statistics of the uniform distribution on the unit interval have marginal distributions belonging to the beta distribution family.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] We also give a simple method to derive the joint distribution of any number of order statistics, and finally translate these results to arbitrary continuous distributions using the cdf.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] We assume throughout this section that $X_{1},X_{2},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are random samples drawn from a continuous distribution with cdf $F_{X}$ .
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Denoting $U_{i}=F_{X}(X_{i})$ we obtain the corresponding random sample $U_{1},\ldots ,U_{n}$ from the standard uniform distribution.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Note that the order statistics also satisfy $U_{(i)}=F_{X}(X_{(i)})$ .
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] that is, the *k*th order statistic of the uniform distribution is a beta-distributed random variable.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The proof of these statements is as follows.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] For $U_{(k)}$ to be between *u* and *u* + *du*, it is necessary that exactly *k* − 1 elements of the sample are smaller than *u*, and that at least one is between *u* and *u* + d*u*.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The probability that more than one is in this latter interval is already $O(du^{2})$ , so we have to calculate the probability that exactly *k* − 1, 1 and *n* − *k* observations fall in the intervals $(0,u)$ , $(u,u+du)$ and $(u+du,1)$ respectively.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The mean of this distribution is *k* / (*n* + 1).
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] One reasons in an entirely analogous way to derive the higher-order joint distributions.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] One way to understand this is that the unordered sample does have constant density equal to 1, and that there are *n*! different permutations of the sample corresponding to the same sequence of order statistics.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] This is related to the fact that 1/*n*! is the volume of the region $0<u_{1}<\cdots <u_{n}<1$ .
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Using the above formulas, one can derive the distribution of the range of the order statistics, that is the distribution of $U_{(n)}-U_{(1)}$ , i.e. maximum minus the minimum.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] where the *Z**j* are i.i.d. standard exponential random variables (i.e. with rate parameter 1).
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] This result was first published by Alfréd Rényi.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The Laplace transform of order statistics may be sampled from an Erlang distribution via a path counting method .
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] An interesting question is how well the order statistics perform as estimators of the quantiles of the underlying distribution.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The simplest case to consider is how well the sample median estimates the population median.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] As an example, consider a random sample of size 6.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] In that case, the sample median is usually defined as the midpoint of the interval delimited by the 3rd and 4th order statistics.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Although the sample median is probably among the best distribution-independent point estimates of the population median, what this example illustrates is that it is not a particularly good one in absolute terms.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] With such a small sample size, if one wants at least 95% confidence, one is reduced to saying that the median is between the minimum and the maximum of the 6 observations with probability 31/32 or approximately 97%.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Size 6 is, in fact, the smallest sample size such that the interval determined by the minimum and the maximum is at least a 95% confidence interval for the population median.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] where *f* is the density function, and *F* −1 is the quantile function associated with *F*.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] One of the first people to mention and prove this result was Frederick Mosteller in his seminal paper in 1946.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Further research led in the 1960s to the Bahadur representation which provides information about the error bounds.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The convergence to normal distribution also holds in a stronger sense, such as convergence in relative entropy or KL divergence.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] An interesting observation can be made in the case where the distribution is symmetric, and the population median equals the population mean.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] In this case, the sample mean, by the central limit theorem, is also asymptotically normally distributed, but with variance σ2*/n* instead.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] This asymptotic analysis suggests that the mean outperforms the median in cases of low kurtosis, and vice versa.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] For example, the median achieves better confidence intervals for the Laplace distribution, while the mean performs better for *X* that are normally distributed.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] with *Zi* being independent identically distributed exponential random variables with rate 1.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Since *X*/*n* and *Y*/*n* are asymptotically normally distributed by the CLT, our results follow by application of the delta method.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The mutual information and f-divergence between order statistics have also been considered.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] For example, if the parent distribution is continuous, then for all $1\leq r,m\leq n$ $I(X_{(r)};X_{(m)})=I(U_{(r)};U_{(m)}),$ In other words, mutual information is independent of the parent distribution.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Moments of the distribution for the first order statistic can be used to develop a non-parametric density estimator.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Suppose, we want to estimate the density $f_{X}$ at the point $x^{*}$ .
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] where Q is the quantile function associated with the distribution $g_{Y}$ , and $\delta _{N}(z)=(N+1)(1-z)^{N}$ .
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] In contrast to the bandwidth/length based tuning parameters for histogram and kernel based approaches, the tuning parameter for the order statistic based density estimator is the size of sample subsets.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Such an estimator is more robust than histogram and kernel based approaches, for example densities like the Cauchy distribution (which lack finite moments) can be inferred without the need for specialized modifications such as IQR based bandwidths.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] This is because the first moment of the order statistic always exists if the expected value of the underlying distribution does, but the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Suppose $X_{1},X_{2},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are i.i.d. random variables from a discrete distribution with cumulative distribution function $F(x)$ and probability mass function $f(x)$ .
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] The problem of computing the *k*th smallest (or largest) element of a list is called the selection problem and is solved by a selection algorithm.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Although this problem is difficult for very large lists, sophisticated selection algorithms have been created that can solve this problem in time proportional to the number of elements in the list, even if the list is totally unordered.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] If the data is stored in certain specialized data structures, this time can be brought down to O(log *n*).
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] In many applications all order statistics are required, in which case a sorting algorithm can be used and the time taken is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] Order statistics have applications in areas like reliability theory, financial mathematics, survival analysis, epidemiology, sports, quality control, and actuarial risk.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] There is an extensive literature devoted to studies on applications of order statistics in these fields.
[src:mann-whitney/order-statistic] For example, a recent application in actuarial risk can be found in, where some weighted premium principles in terms of record claims and kth record claims are provided.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The **sign test** is a statistical test for consistent differences between pairs of observations, such as the weight of subjects before and after treatment.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Given pairs of observations (such as weight pre- and post-treatment) for each subject, the sign test determines if one member of the pair (such as pre-treatment) tends to be greater than (or less than) the other member of the pair (such as post-treatment).
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The paired observations may be designated *x* and *y*.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] For comparisons of paired observations (*x*,y), the sign test is most useful if comparisons can only be expressed as *x* > *y*, *x* = *y*, or *x* < *y*.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] If, instead, the observations can be expressed as numeric quantities (*x* = 7, *y* = 18), or as ranks (rank of *x* = 1st, rank of *y* = 8th), then the paired t-test or the Wilcoxon signed-rank test typically have greater power than the sign test for detecting consistent differences.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] However, they require more stringent assumptions, and when these assumptions are violated, they frequently yield incorrect results.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] If X and Y are quantitative variables, the **sign test** can be used to test the hypothesis that the difference between the *X* and *Y* has zero median, assuming continuous distributions of the two random variables *X* and *Y*, in the situation when we can draw paired samples from *X* and *Y*.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The sign test can also test if the median of a collection of numbers is significantly greater than or less than a specified value.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] For example, given a list of student grades in a class, the sign test can determine if the median grade is significantly different from, say, 75 out of 100.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The sign test is a non-parametric test which makes very few assumptions about the nature of the distributions under test – this means that it has very general applicability but may lack the statistical power of the alternative tests.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The two conditions for the paired-sample sign test are that a sample must be randomly selected from each population, and the samples must be dependent, or paired.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Independent samples cannot be meaningfully paired.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Since the test is nonparametric, the samples need not come from normally distributed populations.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Also, the test works for left-tailed, right-tailed, and two-tailed tests.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] In other words, the null hypothesis states that given a random pair of measurements (*x**i*, *y**i*), then *x**i* and *y**i* are equally likely to be larger than the other.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] To test the null hypothesis, independent pairs of sample data are collected from the populations {(*x*1, *y*1), (*x*2, *y*2), . . ., (*x**n*, *y**n*)}.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Pairs are omitted for which there is no difference so that there is a possibility of a reduced sample of *m* pairs.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Then let *W* be the number of pairs for which *y**i* − *x**i* > 0.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Assuming that H0 is true, then *W* follows a binomial distribution *W* ~ b(*n*, 0.5).
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Each *Zi* comes from the same continuous population.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The values *X**i* and *Y**i* represent are ordered (at least the ordinal scale), so the comparisons "greater than", "less than", and "equal to" are meaningful.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Since the test statistic is expected to follow a binomial distribution, the standard binomial test is used to calculate significance.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The normal approximation to the binomial distribution can be used for large sample sizes, *m* > 25.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The left-tail value is computed by Pr(*W* ≤ *w*), which is the p-value for the alternative H1: *p* < 0.50.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] This alternative means that the *X* measurements tend to be higher.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The right-tail value is computed by Pr(*W* ≥ *w*), which is the p-value for the alternative H1: *p* > 0.50.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] This alternative means that the *Y* measurements tend to be higher.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] For a two-sided alternative H1 the p-value is twice the smaller tail-value.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Zar gives the following example of the sign test for matched pairs.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Data are collected on the length of the left hind leg and left foreleg for 10 deer.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The null hypothesis is that there is no difference between the hind leg and foreleg length in deer.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The alternative hypothesis is that there is a difference between hind leg length and foreleg length.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] This is a two-tailed test, rather than a one-tailed test.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] For the two tailed test, the alternative hypothesis is that hind leg length may be either greater than or less than foreleg length.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] A one-sided test could be that hind leg length is greater than foreleg length, so that the difference can only be in one direction (greater than).
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] There are 8 positive differences and 2 negative differences.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] If the null hypothesis is true, that there is no difference in hind leg and foreleg lengths, then the expected number of positive differences is 5 out of 10.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] What is the probability that the observed result of 8 positive differences, or a more extreme result, would occur if there is no difference in leg lengths?
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Because the test is two-sided, a result as extreme or more extreme than 8 positive differences includes the results of 8, 9, or 10 positive differences, and the results of 0, 1, or 2 positive differences.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The probability of 8 or more positives among 10 deer or 2 or fewer positives among 10 deer is the same as the probability of 8 or more heads or 2 or fewer heads in 10 flips of a fair coin.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The probabilities can be calculated using the binomial test, with the probability of heads = probability of tails = 0.5.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Thus, the probability of observing a results as extreme as 8 of 10 positive differences in leg lengths, if there is no difference in leg lengths, is *p* = 0.109375.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The null hypothesis is not rejected at a significance level of *p* = 0.05.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] With a larger sample size, the evidence might be sufficient to reject the null hypothesis.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Because the observations can be expressed as numeric quantities (actual leg length), the paired t-test or Wilcoxon signed rank test will usually have greater power than the sign test to detect consistent differences.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] For this example, the paired t-test for differences indicates that there is a significant difference between hind leg length and foreleg length (*p* = 0.007).
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] If the observed result was 9 positive differences in 10 comparisons, the sign test would be significant.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Only coin flips with 0, 1, 9, or 10 heads would be as extreme as or more extreme than the observed result.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] In general, 8 of 10 positive differences is not significant (*p* = 0.11), but 9 of 10 positive differences is significant (*p* = 0.0215).
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Conover gives the following example using a one-sided sign test for matched pairs.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] A manufacturer produces two products, A and B.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The manufacturer wishes to know if consumers prefer product B over product A.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] A sample of 10 consumers are each given product A and product B, and asked which product they prefer.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The null hypothesis is that consumers do not prefer product B over product A.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The alternative hypothesis is that consumers prefer product B over product A.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] At the end of the study, 8 consumers preferred product B, 1 consumer preferred product A, and one reported no preference.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The tie is excluded from the analysis, giving n = number of +'s and –'s = 8 + 1 = 9.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] What is the probability of a result as extreme as 8 positives in favor of B in 9 pairs, if the null hypothesis is true, that consumers have no preference for B over A?
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] This is the probability of 8 or more heads in 9 flips of a fair coin, and can be calculated using the binomial distribution with p(heads) = p(tails) = 0.5.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] P(8 or 9 heads in 9 flips of a fair coin) = 0.0195.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The null hypothesis is rejected, and the manufacturer concludes that consumers prefer product B over product A.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Sprent gives the following example of a sign test for a median.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] In a clinical trial, survival time (weeks) is collected for 10 subjects with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The exact survival time was not known for one subject who was still alive after 362 weeks, when the study ended.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The plus sign indicates the subject still alive at the end of the study.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The researcher wished to determine if the median survival time was less than or greater than 200 weeks.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The null hypothesis is that median survival is 200 weeks.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The alternative hypothesis is that median survival is not 200 weeks.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] This is a two-sided test: the alternative median may be greater than or less than 200 weeks.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] If the null hypothesis is true, that the median survival is 200 weeks, then, in a random sample approximately half the subjects should survive less than 200 weeks, and half should survive more than 200 weeks.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Observations below 200 are assigned a minus (−); observations above 200 are assigned a plus (+).
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] For the subject survival times, there are 7 observations below 200 weeks (−) and 3 observations above 200 weeks (+) for the n=10 subjects.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Because any one observation is equally likely to be above or below the population median, the number of plus scores will have a binomial distribution with mean = 0.5.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] What is the probability of a result as extreme as 7 in 10 subjects being below the median?
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] This is exactly the same as the probability of a result as extreme as 7 heads in 10 tosses of a fair coin.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Because this is a two-sided test, an extreme result can be either three or fewer heads or seven or more heads.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The probability for each value of *k* is given in the table below.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Thus, the probability of observing 3 or fewer plus signs or 7 or more plus signs in the survival data, if the median survival is 200 weeks, is 0.3438.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The expected number of plus signs is 5 if the null hypothesis is true.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Observing 3 or fewer, or 7 or more pluses is not significantly different from 5.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Because of the extremely small sample size, this sample has low power to detect a difference.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The sign test is a special case of the binomial test where the probability of success under the null hypothesis is p=0.5.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Thus, the sign test can be performed using the binomial test, which is provided in most statistical software programs.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] On-line calculators for the sign test can be founded by searching for "sign test calculator".
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Many websites offer the binomial test, but generally offer only a two-sided version.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] In R, the binomial test can be performed using the function `binom.test()`.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The sign test example from Zar compared the length of hind legs and forelegs of deer.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The hind leg was longer than the foreleg in 8 of 10 deer.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Thus, there are x=8 successes in n=10 trials.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The hypothesized probability of success (defined as hind leg longer than foreleg) is *p* = 0.5 under the null hypothesis that hind legs and forelegs do not differ in length.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The alternative hypothesis is that hind leg length may be either greater than or less than foreleg length, which is a two sided test, specified as alternative="two.sided".
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The sign test example in Conover examined consumer preference for product A vs. product B.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The null hypothesis was that consumers do not prefer product B over product A.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The alternative hypothesis was that consumers prefer product B over product A, a one-sided test.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] In the study, 8 of 9 consumers who expressed a preference preferred product B over product A.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Conover and Sprent describe John Arbuthnot's use of the sign test in 1710.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Arbuthnot examined birth records in London for each of the 82 years from 1629 to 1710.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] In every year, the number of males born in London exceeded the number of females.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] If the null hypothesis of equal number of births is true, the probability of the observed outcome is 1/282, leading Arbuthnot to conclude that the probability of male and female births were not exactly equal.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] For his publications in 1692 and 1710, Arbuthnot is credited with "… the first use of significance tests …", the first example of reasoning about statistical significance and moral certainty, and "… perhaps the first published report of a nonparametric test …".
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Hald further describes the impact of Arbuthnot's research.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] "Nicholas Bernoulli (1710–1713) completes the analysis of Arbuthnot's data by showing that the larger part of the variation of the yearly number of male births can be explained as binomial with *p* = 18/35.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] This is the first example of fitting a binomial to data.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The sign test requires only that the observations in a pair be ordered, for example *x* > *y*.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] In some cases, the observations for all subjects can be assigned a rank value (1, 2, 3, ...).
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] If the observations can be ranked, and each observation in a pair is a random sample from a symmetric distribution, then the Wilcoxon signed-rank test is appropriate.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The Wilcoxon test will generally have greater power to detect differences than the sign test.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The asymptotic relative efficiency of the sign test to the Wilcoxon signed rank test, under these circumstances, is 0.67.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] If the paired observations are numeric quantities (such as the actual length of the hind leg and foreleg in the Zar example), and the differences between paired observations are random samples from a single normal distribution, then the paired t-test is appropriate.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The paired t-test will generally have greater power to detect differences than the sign test.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] The asymptotic relative efficiency of the sign test to the paired t-test, under these circumstances, is 0.637.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] In some applications, the observations within each pair can only take the values 0 or 1.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] For example, 0 may indicate failure and 1 may indicate success.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] In these cases, the same procedure as the sign test is used, but is known as McNemar's test.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Instead of paired observations such as (Product A, Product B), the data may consist of three or more levels (Product A, Product B, Product C).
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] If the individual observations can be ordered in the same way as for the sign test, for example B > C > A, then the Friedman test may be used.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] Bian, McAleer and Wong proposed in 2011 a non-parametric test for paired data when there are many ties.
[src:mann-whitney/sign-test] They showed that their trinomial test is superior to the sign test in presence of ties.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] In probability theory and statistics, a **stochastic order** quantifies the concept of one random variable being "bigger" than another.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] These are usually partial orders, so that one random variable A may be neither stochastically greater than, less than, nor equal to another random variable B .
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] Many different orders exist, which have different applications.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] where $\Pr(\cdot )$ denotes the probability of an event.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] This is sometimes denoted $A\preceq B$ or $A\leq _{\mathrm {st} }B$ .
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] If additionally $\Pr(A>x)<\Pr(B>x)$ for some x , then A is stochastically strictly less than B , sometimes denoted $A\prec B$ .
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] In decision theory, under this circumstance, B is said to be first-order stochastically dominant over *A*.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] The following rules describe situations when one random variable is stochastically less than or equal to another.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] Strict version of some of these rules also exist.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] If two sequences of random variables $A_{i}$ and $B_{i}$ , with $A_{i}\preceq B_{i}$ for all i each converge in distribution, then their limits satisfy $A\preceq B$ .
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] If A , B and C are random variables such that $\sum _{c}\Pr(C=c)=1$ and $\Pr(A>u\mid C=c)\leq \Pr(B>u\mid C=c)$ for all u and c such that $\Pr(C=c)>0$ , then $A\preceq B$ .
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] If $A\preceq B$ and $\operatorname {E} [A]=\operatorname {E} [B]$ then $A\mathrel {\overset {d}{=}} B$ (the random variables are equal in distribution).
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] There also exist higher-order notions of stochastic dominance.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] With the definitions above, we have $A\prec _{(i)}B\implies A\prec _{(i+1)}B$ .
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] Other types of multivariate stochastic orders exist.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] For instance the upper and lower orthant order which are similar to the usual one-dimensional stochastic order.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] The following stochastic orders are useful in the theory of random social choice.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] They are used to compare the outcomes of random social choice functions, in order to check them for efficiency or other desirable criteria.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] The dominance orders below are ordered from the most conservative to the least conservative.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] They are exemplified on random variables over the finite support {30,20,10}.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] If two variables have the same mean, they can still be compared by how "spread out" their distributions are.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] This is captured to a limited extent by the variance, but more fully by a range of stochastic orders.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] Convex order is a special kind of variability order.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] Under the convex ordering, A is less than B if and only if for all convex u , $\operatorname {E} [u(A)]\leq \operatorname {E} [u(B)]$ .
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] Laplace transform order compares both size and variability of two random variables.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] Similar to convex order, Laplace transform order is established by comparing the expectation of a function of the random variable where the function is from a special class: $u(x)=-\exp(-\alpha x)$ .
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] This makes the Laplace transform order an integral stochastic order with the generator set given by the function set defined above with $\alpha$ a positive real number.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] Considering a family of probability distributions $({P}_{\alpha })_{\alpha \in F}$ on partially ordered space $(E,\preceq )$ indexed with $\alpha \in F$ (where $(F,\preceq )$ is another partially ordered space, the concept of complete or realizable monotonicity may be defined.
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] It means, there exists a family of random variables $(X_{\alpha })_{\alpha }$ on the same probability space, such that the distribution of $X_{\alpha }$ is ${P}_{\alpha }$ and $X_{\alpha }\preceq X_{\beta }$ almost surely whenever $\alpha \preceq \beta$ .
[src:mann-whitney/stochastic-ordering] It means the existence of a monotone coupling.
